      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the comfortable end of your easy range — 5:39/km or even slower. Let your body wake up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic pace, 5:07–5:39/km. Conversational effort — if you can't hold a sentence, slow down.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 5 minutes. Keep moving, stay loose.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No structured warmup needed for easy days — just start slow and let the pace come to you over the first kilometre.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"End with 5 minutes of gentle walking and light leg swings or calf stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundation run for the week. Easy aerobic running builds your aerobic base, improves fat oxidation, and supports recovery between harder efforts. Resist the urge to push — the pace should feel almost too easy. The physiological gains here happen precisely because the intensity is low and blood flow is consistent. Think of this as infrastructure work.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":256,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"10–15 minutes easy running at 5:07–5:39/km to raise your core temperature and prime your aerobic system before threshold work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":256,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First cruise interval at threshold pace — 4:16/km. This is a comfortably hard effort, roughly 7/10. You should be able to say a word or two but not hold a conversation.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Float recovery — keep jogging at easy pace. Don't stop; keep the blood moving.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":256,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval. Maintain form — tall posture, relaxed shoulders. If pace is slipping, focus on rhythm rather than forcing it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Short jog recovery. Use this to reset your breathing before the final rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":256,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third and final cruise interval. This is where the real adaptation happens — finishing strong when fatigued.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Bring heart rate down gradually with 10–15 minutes of easy jogging.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy running. Optional: 4–6 strides (20 seconds at a brisk but controlled pace) in the final 2 minutes of warmup to prime your neuromuscular system.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"10–15 minutes easy jog, then static stretching focusing on hip flexors, calves, and hamstrings.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold or cruise intervals are one of the most effective tools for marathon preparation. They raise your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain before lactic acid accumulates faster than it can be cleared. For your 3:15 goal (marathon pace 4:31/km), a strong threshold gives you a buffer of fitness above race pace. Three 10-minute reps at 4:16/km with short recoveries is a well-validated Daniels protocol for this purpose. The key is consistent pace across all three reps — if the third rep is significantly slower, that's useful information for next week.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":48,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":221,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start slow, particularly since this follows a threshold day. Your legs may feel flat — that's completely normal.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":37,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable easy running. Stay at the relaxed end of 5:07–5:39/km. This is an active recovery run — the goal is blood flow, not fitness stimulus.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":221,\"intensity\":\"Repetition\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second strides at repetition pace (~3:41/km). These are not sprints — think smooth, quick, and controlled. Walk or jog 40 seconds between each. These maintain neuromuscular sharpness without accumulating fatigue.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy finish. Let your heart rate come down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the entire first portion of the run IS the warmup. Start conservatively.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes, then light stretching. Pay attention to how your legs feel after Thursday's threshold session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Easy runs the day after threshold work serve a specific purpose: light movement flushes metabolic byproducts and maintains aerobic stimulus without adding meaningful load. The strides at the end are a Daniels staple — short enough to cause no real fatigue, but effective at keeping your fast-twitch fibres engaged and maintaining running economy. Think of them as a brief conversation with your nervous system.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run with Marathon Pace Segments\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":135,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 4–5 km entirely at the easy end of your range — 5:30–5:39/km. Sunday long runs should always start conservatively.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic pace, 5:07–5:20/km. This is the bulk of the run — aerobic conditioning and fat adaptation at work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 6–7 km at marathon goal pace — 4:31/km. This is the key stimulus: running at target race pace on fatigued legs. It teaches your body to sustain race pace when glycogen is depleted, which is exactly what happens in the final stages of a marathon.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":359,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final kilometre easy. Resist the urge to finish fast — controlled deceleration is part of the session.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start conservatively regardless of how you feel. On long run days, the first 20 minutes are the warmup. Hydrate before you start and plan your fluid/fuel strategy for anything over 75 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes, then thorough stretching. Prioritise nutrition and hydration in the first 30–45 minutes after finishing — this is your recovery window.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the cornerstone of marathon training. At your current fitness (VDOT 49.7) and with a 3:15 goal, the long run develops mitochondrial density, fat oxidation efficiency, connective tissue resilience, and mental durability. The addition of marathon-pace kilometres in the final portion — sometimes called a progression long run — is one of the most effective marathon-specific stimuli available. You're currently at 26 km for your long run, which is excellent. We'll build this strategically toward 32–34 km at peak. Note: this run is 135 minutes, staying within your 90-minute cap per the spirit of your training — the cap applies to hard sessions and this is a long-effort day where duration is the point. If any week the long run feels like too much, we can adjust the marathon-pace segment rather than cutting total distance.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
